  "text": "The PromQL query parsing and validation pipeline in prometheus/prometheus is implemented through several coordinated components:\n\n## Parser Interface and Implementation\nThe `promql/parser/parse.go` file defines the `Parser` interface which provides PromQL parsing methods, particularly `ParseExpr(input string) (Expr, error)`. The interface implementation uses an internal `parser` struct that orchestrates the complete parsing workflow. The `parser` struct contains a `Lexer` instance, manages function lookups, and coordinates the generated parser through `parseGenerated` method calls.\n\n## Lexer and Tokenization\nThe `promql/parser/lex.go` file contains the `Lexer` struct which performs the tokenization step by scanning input strings and emitting `Item` objects. The lexer maintains internal state including parenthesis depth, brace open status, and bracket open status to properly handle nested expressions. Token types are defined by the `ItemType` enum which includes operators (ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, etc.), aggregators (SUM, AVG, COUNT, etc.), and keywords (AND, OR, BY, etc.).\n\n## AST Node Type Definitions\nThe `promql/parser/ast.go` file defines the complete Abstract Syntax Tree structure:\n- `Expr` interface: Generic interface implemented by all expression types\n- `Node` interface: Base interface for all AST nodes with String(), Pretty(), and PositionRange() methods\n- Expression types: `VectorSelector`, `BinaryExpr`, `AggregateExpr`, `Call`, `MatrixSelector`, `SubqueryExpr`, `NumberLiteral`, `ParenExpr`, `StringLiteral`, `UnaryExpr`, `DurationExpr`, `StepInvariantExpr`\n- Vector matching: `VectorMatching` struct describing how elements are matched in binary operations, and `VectorMatchCardinality` enum (CardOneToOne, CardManyToOne, CardOneToMany, CardManyToMany)\n\n## Type Validation System\nThe `promql/parser/value.go` file defines the value type system with `ValueType` constants (ValueTypeVector, ValueTypeScalar, ValueTypeMatrix, ValueTypeString, ValueTypeNone) and the `Value` interface. Each expression node implements a `Type()` method that returns its ValueType. The `checkAST` method in parse.go performs type checking by recursively validating that expressions match their expected types.\n\n## Function Registry\nThe `promql/parser/functions.go` file maintains a `Functions` map containing all supported PromQL functions. Each function is defined as a `Function` struct with Name, ArgTypes (slice of ValueType), Variadic flag, ReturnType, and Experimental flag. This registry is loaded into each parser instance and used during AST validation to verify function call arguments.\n\n## Generated Yacc Parser\nThe `promql/parser/generated_parser.y` file contains the YACC grammar rules that define PromQL's syntax. It includes:\n- Token definitions for all operators, aggregators, keywords, and literals\n- Grammar rules for expressions, binary operations, function calls, and aggregations\n- Type definitions mapping grammar symbols to Go types\nThe generated Go code is output to `promql/parser/generated_parser.y.go` which implements the actual parsing logic. Parser entry points include START_EXPRESSION, START_METRIC, START_METRIC_SELECTOR, and START_SERIES_DESCRIPTION.\n\n## Feature Registration System\nThe `promql/parser/features.go` file implements `RegisterFeatures` method which registers all PromQL capabilities with a feature registry, including operators, aggregators, functions, and experimental features. This enables feature tracking for prometheus configuration options like EnableExperimentalFunctions.\n\n## Engine Integration\nThe `promql/engine.go` file defines the `Engine` struct which integrates the parser as part of the complete query execution pipeline. The Engine uses a `parser.Parser` instance (configured via `EngineOpts`) to parse query strings before execution. The `QueryEngine` interface defines the contract for query execution with methods like `NewInstantQuery` and `NewRangeQuery`.\n\n## Position Range Tracking\nThe `promql/parser/posrange/posrange.go` file provides position tracking capabilities used by the lexer and parser to maintain accurate error reporting with line and column information.\n\n## Complete Flow\nThe parsing flow follows this chain: `ParseExpr` (Parser interface) → `parseExpr` (internal method) → `parseGenerated` (YACC-generated parser) → `checkAST` (type validation) → returns validated `Expr` AST. Errors are accumulated in `ParseErrors` list with full position context for diagnostics."
